<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<!--
  entitlements applied by both build.sh
  (ad-hoc, CI/headless only ‚Äî see below) and the Xcode project (real
  Apple Development signing, the path that actually works end to end).

  CONFIRMED WORKING end-to-end on a real macOS 15.7.7 VM: overlay badge
  renders in Finder, and the "yadorilink" context submenu (View sync
  status/Pause/Resume/Pin/Evict) appears and is wired to the Rust FFI
  core. Getting here took three fixes, all load-bearing:

  1. App Sandbox must be ON. PlugInKit refuses to even discover an
     unsandboxed FinderSync extension ("plug-ins must be sandboxed").
  2. A real signature is required to *launch* a sandboxed extension at
     all ‚Äî ad-hoc signing (build.sh's `codesign --sign -`) lets the
     process spawn but it dies silently right after AppSandbox init,
     before any application code runs. Only a real "Apple Development"
     (or better) signing identity, from a paid Apple Developer Program
     team, fixes this. Xcode's automatic signing also requires every
     *device that will run the build* to be registered with the team
     (Certificates, Identifiers & Profiles ‚Üí Devices) ‚Äî a stale/scoped
     provisioning profile fails with "Provisioning profile does not
     allow this device" and the extension won't launch on an
     unregistered machine even with valid signing.
  3. Reaching the daemon's socket from inside the sandbox needs
     com.apple.security.application-groups, not
     com.apple.security.temporary-exception.files.absolute-path.
     read-write (tried first, matching the daemon's normal
     `~/Library/Application Support/yadorilink` socket location) ‚Äî that
     consistently failed with EPERM despite a correct path, a real
     signature, and the entitlement being visibly present in the signed
     binary (`codesign -d --entitlements`). Likely needs Apple's
     case-by-case approval beyond a personal Developer Program
     membership, unlike App Sandbox or App Groups (both standard,
     freely available capabilities). App Groups additionally requires
     Xcode to auto-register an App ID / group ID with the team the
     first time it's used (may itself need `-allowProvisioningUpdates`
     and a stale local provisioning-profile cache cleared ‚Äî see
     `~/Library/Developer/Xcode/UserData/Provisioning Profiles/` ‚Äî if a
     newly-added device or capability doesn't show up in a rebuild).

  The resolved App Group container path has NO Team ID prefix ‚Äî despite
  matching the `~/Library/Containers/<TeamID>.<bundle-id>/` convention
  App Sandbox itself uses, `FileManager.default.
  containerURL(forSecurityApplicationGroupIdentifier:)` resolves this
  App Group to plain `~/Library/Group Containers/group.com.yadorilink.
  shared/` ‚Äî confirmed by having the extension call that API directly
  and write the result to a file; guessing the Team-ID-prefixed form
  first cost real debugging time. `shell-ext/macos/core/src/ipc_client.
  rs`'s `APP_GROUP_CONTAINER` constant must match this exactly.

  The daemon itself isn't sandboxed, so it needs no entitlement to write
  into the group container ‚Äî it's just told to via
  YADORILINK_SHELL_IPC_SOCKET, an ordinary filesystem path from its point
  of view. Moving the daemon's *default* socket location to the group
  container (vs. requiring this env var override) is a real product
  decision belonging to yadorilink-daemon, not made here.
-->
<dict>
	<key>com.apple.security.app-sandbox</key>
	<true/>
	<key>com.apple.security.network.client</key>
	<false/>
	<key>com.apple.security.network.server</key>
	<false/>
	<key>com.apple.security.application-groups</key>
	<array>
		<string>group.com.juntaki.yadorilink.shared</string>
	</array>
</dict>
</plist>
